name: Sonny Baker
describe: He joined the Somerset Academy last Autumn and featured in the England Development Under 19 Programme North v South Matches. He is also another player alongside the extended list of those currently on the Somerset playing staff, who have represented and played National Counties cricket for Devon NCCA

name: Tom Banton
describe: Tom enjoyed an amazing 2019 season, in which he scored a maiden T20 and List A hundred. He won Somerset’s White Ball Player of the Year, the PCA Young Cricketer of the Year and the coveted Cricket Writers Club Young Cricketer of the Year Award.

name: George Bartlett
describe: Steve Snell is the SCCC Head of Talent Pathway. “Im delighted for Sonny,” he said. “Sonny has put in an unbelievable amount of work into earning an opportunity both physically and mentally. He has also conscientiously managed significant educational commitments.

name: Jack Brooks
describe: In 2016 George scored a century for England Under 19s against Sri Lanka and played for Somerset in the finals of both the 2nd XI T20 and 2nd XI Trophy competitions. George made his Championship debut in the match at Edgbaston against Warwickshire.

name: Josh Davey
describe: He has also taken 37 List A wickets at an average of 34.48 with a best of three for 30 and 47 T20 wickets at an average of 27.27 with a best of five for 21.Jack played a vital role in Yorkshires County Championship.

name: Steven Davise
describe: Jack first season for Somerset was interrupted through injuries but he still made crucial contributions throughout a successful County Championship campaign. He ran through the Surrey line-up on the final day at Guildford to claim his maiden 5-wicket-haul for the Club and was a consistent threat with the new ball in his hand.

name: Lewis Goldsworthy
describe: Josh has an impressive career playing for Scotland and has appeared in 29 ODIs and 14 T20s. In January 2015 he took 6 for 28 and scored an unbeaten 53 to help Scotland beat Afghanistan in a triangular series. He also enjoyed considerable success with the ball at the 2015 World Cup and at one stage was the leading wicket-taker.

name: Michael Cook
describe: 2016 saw Josh making his Championship debut for Somerset in the opening match of the season against Durham, but most of his appearances were once again limited to one day cricket In 2017 Josh played in three Championship matches, in one of which he scored 47, his best for Somerset.
